1. Understanding Data's Shape (Distributions)

When you first look at a single column of numerical data (Univariate Analysis), you want to understand its shape using a Histogram or Distplot (KDE)
If the graph looks like a symmetrical bell curve: You suspect it follows a Gaussian (Normal) Distribution
.
To absolutely confirm it is Gaussian: You can't just trust your eyes. 
You go for a Q-Q Plot. If the data points lie on a straight diagonal line against theoretical normal values, it is Gaussian
-You can also check Skewness and Kurtosis (both should be close to 0),or run a One-Sample KS Test
If it IS Gaussian: You unlock the Empirical Rule (68.2% - 95% - 99.7%). You can use this rule to easily find outliers (anything beyond the 3rd standard deviation is an outlier)
.
If it is NOT Gaussian: The empirical rule will fail.
Instead, you must go for Chebyshev’s Inequality to find where your data ranges lie

If the graph has a long tail to the right (Right-Skewed): You go for a Log Transformation.
If you apply log(X) to your data and the new graph becomes a perfect Gaussian bell curve, your original data was a Log-Normal Distribution

2. Finding Relationships Between Variables

When you are looking at two columns of data (Bivariate Analysis), you start by drawing a Scatter Plot to visually spot a relationship
If you want to know if one variable increases when the other increases: You go for Covariance. However, 
covariance only tells you the direction (positive or negative), not how strong the relationship is.

Because Covariance lacks scale: You upgrade to the Pearson Correlation Coefficient (PCC), which gives you a clean score between -1 and 1
If the scatter plot shows a curve (Non-Linear): Pearson Correlation will fail because it only works well for straight lines.
Instead, you go for the Spearman Rank Correlation, which uses the ranks of the data rather than the actual values to handle non-linear relationships
.
If both variables are Categorical (e.g., Gender vs. Survived): You cannot use scatter plots or correlation. Instead,
you go for a Chi-Square Test using a contingency table to prove if the two categories are related or independent

3. Comparing Two Entire Datasets

If you want to know if two separate columns (or train vs. test data) behave the exact same way: You go for the Two-Sample KS Test.
This test compares the Empirical Cumulative Distribution Function (ECDF) of both datasets.
If the difference between their curves is too large, they do not share the same distribution


4. Guessing Population Data from a Small Sample
In real life, you rarely have data for the entire population, only a sample
If you need to guess the population average from a sample: You rely on the Central Limit Theorem (CLT).
The CLT states that if you take enough samples (n ≥ 30), the distribution of those sample means will look Gaussian, allowing you to estimate the true population mean (this is called Point Estimation)
.
Because a single point estimate isn't perfectly safe: You go for a Confidence Interval (CI).
Instead of saying the average height is exactly 170cm, you say "I am 95% confident the average height is between 168cm and 172cm"
.
If you don't know your data's underlying distribution at all to make a CI: You go for Empirical Bootstrapping.
This is a modern technique where you repeatedly take random samples with replacement from your existing data to simulate a distribution and find your confidence intervals

5. Proving a Claim (Hypothesis Testing)

If you want to prove a business claim with solid evidence (e.g., "A glucose tablet cures headaches"): You go for Hypothesis Testing. 
You set a Null Hypothesis (H0: "The tablet does nothing") and an Alternate Hypothesis (H1: "The tablet cures headaches")
.
To decide which hypothesis is true: You calculate a p-value. If the p-value is very small (usually < 5%), you reject the Null Hypothesis and accept your claim
.
If your sample size is very small: Traditional tests might fail. Instead, you go for a Permutation Test, which is a non-parametric test that shuffles the data to find the p-value
